2 T is D
In the sentence, Betty bought a bit of better butter, the
Ts are in weak positions, so they sound like soft Ds.
Repeat the sentence slowly, word by word. Beddy . badə
. bidə . bedder. budder. Feel the tip of your tongue flick
across that ridge behind your top teeth. Think of the music
of a cello when you say, Betty bought a bit of better butter.
In most languages, the R touches behind the teeth, so you
are in luck with the American T. Just make an association in
your mind, so that when you see a middle position T, you
automatically give it your native R sound. Say, Beri bara bira
with your native accent.
Betty Bought A Bit of Better Butter
Betty bought a bit of better
butter,
But, said she,
This butter's bitter.
If I put it my batter,
It'll make my batter bitter.
Beddy bä də bihad bedder
budder,
Bu(t), said she,
This butter'z bidder.
If I püdi din my bædder,
Id'll make my bædder bidder.
2 T is Held Back
At the end of a word, don't pop the T. It will make you sound upset or arrogant.
Let your tongue go to the T position, but don't let the air pop out

that
it
not

Six Comprehensive T Rules

1. T at the begining of a word is T
Ted, take, ten
2. T in the middle of a word is D
little, water, better
3. T at the end of a word is held, and isn't popped
hot, what, put
4. T is held in words ending in -tain and -ten
certain, written
5. T is held before W, R, L, G and Y
what was, not right, that was, dot com, get-go, that year
6. T is silent after N with lax vowels
interview, interrupt, percentage
1 Top of the Staircase
T is T at the begining of a word, or in a stressed syllable.
Make sure the Ts are sharp and clear.
Tina tried to tame Ted's tiger on Tuesday.
Terry told Tim to take a trip to Texas.
Tom and Tasha were too tense to tango in Taiwan
Tell Tyler to take two turns this time.
Thirteen and fourteen and fifteen make forty two.
2 Middle of the Staircase
T is D in the middle of a word.
Make sure that the Ts between vowels sound like a D.
Patty got a little better.
Put a little water on it.
Eddie was a little better.
Betty put a sweater on.
Get a better water heater.
The meeting was at one.
The brittle metal snapped.
Let him wait a little bit.
He put a lot of butter on.
Go get a letter opener.
[pædee gädə liddl beddr]
[püdə liddl wädr änit]
[eddy wəzə liddl biddr].
[beddy püdə sweddr än]
[gedda beddr wädr heedr]
[thə meeding wəzət wən]
[thə briddl meddl snæpt]
[leddim weidə liddl bit]
[he püdə lädə bəddr än]
[go geddə leddr opənr]
3 T is Held Back
T is held at the end of a word. Put your tongue in
the T position, but do NOT let the air escape.
Take i(t).
It's wha(t) they wan(t) to ge(t).
Pu(t) them back in the po(t)
Se(t) the clock back a(t) the even(t).
Wha(t) did you find a(t) tha(t) site?
4 T is   held in -tain and -ten endings.
Words ending in -tain and -ten have a held T. Why? Because
the tongue position for T and N are so close in the mouth that
they just stick together. Don’t pop the T. Put the tongue in the T
position, but don't release the tongue tip from the top of your
mouth. Let the air escape through your nose.
Remember, there is no popped T and no ə in between.
We tried to shorten the kindergarten class.
Courtney had written about the fountain of youth.
The sumo wrestlers had eaten well to fatten up.
Whitney's rotten kitten has bitten Martin!
They've eaten a lot of chutney in Britain.
The molten lava poured down the mountain.
Brittany's certain that the satin mitten is near the curtain.
We'd forgotten what was written about lightening.
He wanted to whiten, brighten and straighten his teeth
The threatening look heightened the tension in the Continental.
5 T is  held before W, R, K, G and Y
Pat wen(t) west to ge(t) one.
Wha(t) was tha(t) one?
He says tha(t) when we ge(t) we(t) we can'(t) wear white(t)
He wro(t)e reports on the qui(t) claim in the Spo(t) light.
Ge(t) Greg to le(t) Carrie pu(t) water in tha(t) well.
It's no(t) right that the meeting's a(t) one.
Pu(t) one at Wendy's station.
Don'(t) let work ge(t) you down.
I can'(t) wait to have ho(t) cakes.
Mat(t) works too hard at that do(t) com start up.

6 Silent T Practice     (Part 2 of 3)
He is interrupted twenty interviews in Toronto.
[hee(y)innerrupt'd twenny innerviews in tränno]

There was a large percentage of international students.
[there w'z a large percen'j of innernational students]

He won't even interfere with the interaction.
[he won neev'n innerfere with the inneraction]

We took full advantage of the Internet.
[we tük füll advan'j of thee(y)innernet]

He drove the interstate through to Atlanta.
[he drove thee(y)innerstate through to atlænna]

Is he a 'has been' or a 'wanna be'?
[izze a hæz bin ora wanna be]
